## Getting started with Chef

If you're new to Chef, read [How to learn Chef](/skills/how-to-learn-chef/) to learn how to get started, what to do first and where to go next.

Before you approach Chef Automate, we recommend first working through these 3 tutorials.

* [Learn the Chef basics](/tutorials/learn-the-basics/)
* [Manage a node](/tutorials/manage-a-node/)
* [Develop locally](/tutorials/local-development/)

In these tutorials, you'll learn how:

* Chef's _test and repair_ approach keeps your systems in line with the policies you describe.
* _cookbooks_, _receipes_, and _resources_ enable you to express your configuration policy through code.
* the Chef server acts as a central repository for your cookbooks and for information about your servers, or _nodes_.
* the Chef Development Kit (Chef DK) enables you to develop cookbooks, test them locally, and administer your network, all from your workstation.

Although Chef [runs on many platforms](https://docs.chef.io/platforms.html), each tutorial provides content for Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Windows Server, and Ubuntu to give you a sense of how Chef applies to each of these common server environments.

In the first tutorial, _Learn the Chef basics_, the free virtual machine option is the fastest way to get started. In the second tutorial, _Manage a node_, Hosted Chef is an easy way to get started. After you complete these tutorials, you can work through them a second time on your own infrastructure to see how Chef runs in your environment.

